

The centre is \(1\).
The numbered cells are placed on concentric hexagonal rings.
The largest number in the ring of radius \(k\) is the *centered hexagonal number*

\[
H_k = 3k(k+1)+1 .
\]

Hence the ring containing a number \(N\) is the smallest \(k\) with  
\(N\le H_k\).

For \(N=2026\)

\[
H_{25}=3\cdot25\cdot26+1=1951,\qquad 
H_{26}=3\cdot26\cdot27+1=2107,
\]

so \(2026\) lies in the ring \(k=26\).

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 1.  Coordinates of a number

Use the cubic coordinates \((x,y,z)\) with \(x+y+z=0\) and the six
neighbour directions  

\[
\begin{aligned}
E &: (+1,-1,0),   & NE &: (+1,0,-1),\\
NW&: (0,+1,-1), & W &: (-1,+1,0),\\
SW&: (-1,0,+1),  & SE&: (0,-1,+1).
\end{aligned}
\]

Starting the spiral with \(2\) at \((k,-k,0)\) (the eastmost cell of the
ring) and then moving in the order  

\[
NW,\;W,\;SW,\;SE,\;E,\;NE,
\]

each of the five first sides contributes exactly \(k\) cells, the last
side contributes \(k-1\) new cells (the last step returns to the start).

Thus a number \(n\) in the ring \(k\) can be written as  

\[
n= 3(k-1)k+2+\;2k+u\qquad (1\le u\le k)
\]

when it lies on the *south‑west* side of the ring
(the side whose points satisfy \(y=k\) and \(x<0\)).
The parameter \(u=-x\) tells how far along that side the cell is.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 2.  Position of \(2026\)

For \(k=26\)

\[
\text{start}_k =3\cdot25\cdot26+2=1952,
\qquad
2026-1952 = 74 .
\]

Since \(2k=52\), the remainder \(74-52=22\) gives \(u=22\); therefore  

\[
2026 = 1952 + 2\cdot26 + 22 .
\]

So \(2026\) indeed sits on the south‑west side of the \(26\)‑th ring.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 3.  The six neighbours

Let a point on that side have the cubic coordinates  

\[
(-u,\;k,\;-k+u),\qquad k\ge 1,\;1\le u\le k .
\]

Its six neighbours are obtained by adding the six direction vectors:

\[
\begin{array}{ccl}
E   &:& (-u+1,\;k-1,\;-k+u),\\[2pt]
NE  &:& (-u+1,\;k,\;-k+u-1),\\[2pt]
NW  &:& (-u,\;k+1,\;-k+u-1),\\[2pt]
W   &:& (-u-1,\;k+1,\;-k+u),\\[2pt]
SW  &:& (-u-1,\;k,\;-k+u+1),\\[2pt]
SE  &:& (-u,\;k-1,\;-k+u+1).
\end{array}
\]

All of them lie again on a south‑west side of a ring:
the two outer neighbours belong to ring \(k+1\) with parameters \(u\) and
\(u+1\);
the two inner neighbours belong to ring \(k-1\) with parameters
\(u-1\) and \(u\);
the two neighbours on the same ring have parameters \(u-1\) and
\(u+1\).

Using the expression (1) for a number on that side, the neighbour values are

\[
\begin{aligned}
&\bigl[3(k-2)(k-1)+2\bigr] + 2(k-1) + (u-1),\\
&\bigl[3(k-2)(k-1)+2\bigr] + 2(k-1) + u,\\[2pt]
&\bigl[3(k-1)k+2\bigr]       + 2k       + (u-1),\\
&\bigl[3(k-1)k+2\bigr]       + 2k       + (u+1),\\[2pt]
&\bigl[3k(k+1)+2\bigr]        + 2(k+1)   + u,\\
&\bigl[3k(k+1)+2\bigr]        + 2(k+1)   + (u+1).
\end{aligned}
\]

Adding all six gives a spectacular simplification:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\text{Sum} &=
6n + 12 .
\end{aligned}
\]

So **every number that lies on the south‑west side of the ring has its
six neighbours summing to \(6n+12\).**

--------------------------------------------------------------------
### 4.  Applying to \(2026\)

\[
\text{Sum of neighbours of }2026 = 6\cdot2026 + 12
= 12156 + 12
= \boxed{12168}.
\]

(Indeed the individual neighbours are
\(1873,1874,2025,2027,2184,2185\); their sum is \(12168\).)
